<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='462000' id='t-462000'>And so one way to formulate that is</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='464000' id='t-464000'>the human mind can take in millions of pieces of information a minute,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='467000' id='t-467000'>of which it can be consciously aware of about 40.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='470000' id='t-470000'>And this leads to oddities.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='472000' id='t-472000'>One of my favorite is that people named Dennis</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='474000' id='t-474000'>are disproportionately likely to become dentists,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='477000' id='t-477000'>people named Lawrence become lawyers,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='479000' id='t-479000'>because unconsciously we gravitate toward things</span>
